  <li>Эльконин Д.Б. Психология игры. — М.: Владос, 1999.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Как universum. помогает специалисту работать по пяти сферам</h2>
<p>Вместо того чтобы держать в голове ASQ, Bayley, отечественные методики и таблицы возрастных норм, специалист получает единое пространство:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Диагностика</strong> — тесты развития (<a href="https://unvrsm.ru/features">/features</a>) автоматически раскладывают результаты по пяти сферам с указанием возрастной нормы;</li>
  <li><strong>Планирование</strong> — задания в рабочем месте ребёнка помечены цветом сферы, поэтому легко собрать сбалансированный курс;</li>
  <li><strong>Отчётность</strong> — заключения ППк и характеристики (<a href="https://unvrsm.ru/for-specialists">/for-specialists</a>) формируются с корректной терминологией по каждой сфере;</li>
  <li><strong>Родители</strong> — в бесплатном кабинете (<a href="https://unvrsm.ru/for-parents">/for-parents</a>) видят прогресс ребёнка в виде радара и понимают, над чем работает специалист.</li>
</ul>
<p>Подписка для специалистов — 330 ₽/мес, для организаций — 2 500 ₽/мес. Кабинет родителя — бесплатно. Подробности на странице <a href="https://unvrsm.ru/pricing">тарифов</a>.</p>
$RU$,
  'The 5 developmental domains: scientific basis and international approaches',
  'Motor, speech, cognitive, social and emotional — five interconnected developmental lines that form the core of every child card in universum. We review the scientific basis of each and compare with US, UK, German and Finnish frameworks.',
$EN$
<p><strong>In universum. every child card is organised around five developmental domains: motor skills, speech, cognition, social interaction and emotions.</strong> This is not our invention — it is a working translation between the Russian tradition (Vygotsky, Zaporozhets, Elkonin) and international screening frameworks (Bayley, ASQ, Denver II, EYFS). Below we describe the evidence behind each domain and show how the same construct is called in other countries.</p>

<h2>Why five domains</h2>
<p>Child development is holistic, but for diagnostics and lesson planning it helps to break it into measurable lines. Five domains are the minimum set that:</p>
<ul>
  <li>match the <strong>WHO Nurturing Care Framework (2018)</strong>, where "early learning" splits into cognitive, language and social-emotional strands;</li>
  <li>map onto the five domains of <strong>Ages &amp; Stages Questionnaires (ASQ-3)</strong>: communication, gross motor, fine motor, problem solving, personal-social;</li>
  <li>align with <strong>Bayley Scales of Infant and Toddler Development (Bayley-4, 2019)</strong>: cognitive, language, motor, social-emotional, adaptive behaviour.</li>
</ul>

<h2>1. Motor</h2>
<p><strong>Includes:</strong> gross motor (balance, coordination, walking, jumping) and fine motor (grip, writing, scissors). Coded blue in universum. and linked to sensorimotor integration tasks.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence.</strong> Diamond (2000, 2013) showed that the cerebellum and prefrontal cortex mature in sync, so coordination training improves executive function. Meta-analysis by Álvarez-Bueno et al. (Pediatrics, 2017) confirmed an average d ≈ 0.35 effect of physical activity on academic skills in children aged 4–13. In Russian tradition Luria's motor tests (Head, reciprocal coordination) remain part of neuropsychological assessment.</p>
<p><strong>Names abroad:</strong> Gross / Fine Motor (US); Physical Development (UK EYFS, prime area); Motorische Entwicklung (Germany); Kasvan, liikun, kehityn (Finland VASU-2022).</p>

<h2>2. Speech</h2>
<p><strong>Includes:</strong> receptive and expressive speech, phonemic awareness, connected speech.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence.</strong> Hart &amp; Risley (1995) documented the "30-million-word gap" by age 3. Kuhl (Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 2004) mapped sensitive periods for phonemic perception before 12 months. Russian benchmarks come from Gvozdev's stages and Levina's classification of speech underdevelopment (ONR I–IV), which universum. uses in formal reports.</p>
<p><strong>Abroad:</strong> Communication (US), Language and Literacy (UK), Sprache (Germany), Kielten rikas maailma (Finland). The MacArthur-Bates CDI is translated into 100+ languages and serves as an international reference.</p>

<h2>3. Cognition</h2>
<p><strong>Includes:</strong> attention, memory, perception, thinking, executive functions.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence.</strong> Miyake et al. (2000) defined the three-component EF model (inhibition, working memory, shifting). Diamond &amp; Lee (Science, 2011) showed EF training in preschool predicts school success better than IQ. Russian foundation: Vygotsky's zone of proximal development and Galperin's stepwise formation of mental actions — both are baked into task structure in the child workspace.</p>
<p><strong>Abroad:</strong> Problem Solving / Cognitive (ASQ, Bayley), Understanding the World (EYFS), Kognitive Entwicklung (Germany), Tutkin ja toimin ympäristössäni (Finland).</p>

<h2>4. Social interaction</h2>
<p><strong>Includes:</strong> joint attention, Theory of Mind, symbolic and role play, rule following, peer cooperation.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence.</strong> Bowlby &amp; Ainsworth — attachment theory as the base of social development. Baron-Cohen et al. (1985) — the Sally-Anne task for Theory of Mind is still the global standard. Tomasello (2009, "Why We Cooperate") — prosocial behaviour in early childhood. Russian tradition: Elkonin's leading-activity concept — role play is the preschool driver of self-regulation and social norms.</p>
<p><strong>Abroad:</strong> Personal-Social (ASQ), Social-Emotional (Bayley), PSED (UK), Soziale Entwicklung (Germany), Minä ja meidän yhteisömme (Finland).</p>

<h2>5. Emotions</h2>
<p><strong>Includes:</strong> emotion recognition, regulation, empathy, frustration tolerance.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence.</strong> Durlak et al. (Child Development, 2011) — school SEL programmes yield an 11-percentile-point gain in academic performance. The CASEL framework is the de-facto global SEL standard (self-awareness, self-management, social awareness, relationship skills, responsible decision-making). Russian line: Zaporozhets on emotional anticipation and Smirnova on preschool volition.</p>
<p><strong>Abroad emotions usually merge with the social domain:</strong> SEL (US), PSED (UK), Emotionale Entwicklung (Germany). Finland separately highlights <em>tunnetaidot</em> — "emotional skills" — as a key preschool competence.</p>

<h2>Side-by-side comparison</h2>
